(a)For more information about family mediation and to find the nearest mediation service (including those providing a MIAM): www.familymediationcouncil.org.uk (opens in a new tab) ;


(b) For a Guide about children and the family courts for separating parents (including representing yourself in court): the form ‘CB7’: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guide-for-separated-parents-children-and-the-family-courts-cb7/guide-for-separated-parents-children-and-the-family-courts-cb7 (opens in a new tab)


(c) For Cafcass (England): Parenting together – Cafcass – Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (opens in a new tab) ;


(d) For Cafcass Cymru (Wales): Cafcass Cymru: Information about separated parents | GOV.WALES (opens in a new tab) ;


(e) To find a legal adviser or family mediator: http://find-legal-advice.justice.gov.uk (opens in a new tab) ;


(f) To check whether you can get financial help (legal aid) to pay for non-court dispute resolution, &/or advice and representation at court, and to find a legal aid solicitor or mediator: https://www.gov.uk/check-legal-aid (opens in a new tab)


(g) For general advice about sorting out arrangements for children, the use of post-separation mediation, &/or going to court: http://www.advicenow.org.uk (opens in a new tab) ; http://www.advicenow.org.uk/advicenow-guides/family/sorting-out-arrangements-for-your-children/ (opens in a new tab)


(h) For general advice about sorting out arrangements for children: http://theparentconnection.org.uk/ (opens in a new tab)


(i) For advice about Contact Centres, which are neutral places where children of separated families can enjoy contact with their non-resident parents and sometimes other family members, in a comfortable and safe environment; and information about where they are: www.naccc.org.uk (opens in a new tab) ;


(j) For the form to apply for a child arrangements order: https://www.gov.uk/looking-after-children-divorce/apply-for-court-order (opens in a new tab) ;
